+     * file's own PostDrawHook comment above) is the opening storybook's
+     * own 3D backdrop, drawn behind the book (OpeningMdlId[1], untouched,
+     * separately confirmed rotated -- NOT extruded) and unrelated to the
+     * character/story-texture layer (OpeningMdlId[2], layer 0, its own
+     * PreDrawHook camera, feeds the native BookFrameBuf capture --
+     * explicitly out of scope). HSF diagnostic dump found OpeningMdlId[0]
+     * loads the EXACT SAME underlying HSF asset as fileseldll/filesel.c's
+     * own storybook backdrop (identical sub-object names, identical
+     * bitmap names, identical computed hierarchical center) -- see that
+     * file's own comment on this same call for the full CLAMP-vs-REPEAT
+     * finding, which applies here unchanged. OpeningMdlId[0]'s own
+     * top-level transform is confirmed unrotated. Camera unchanged (the
+     * native PreDrawHook / widened PostDrawHook below, both untouched by
+     * this change). */
+    mp6_widescreen_extrude_model(OpeningMdlId[0]);
@@ -522,2 +545,24 @@
-    Hu3DCameraPerspectiveSet(OPENING_CAMERA_BIT, 30.f, 20.f, 15000.f, 1.2f);
-    Hu3DCameraViewportSet(OPENING_CAMERA_BIT, 0.0f, 0.0f, 640.f, 480.f, 0.0f, 1.0f);
+    /* This camera bit is shared by two layers with opposite needs.
+     * PreDrawHook (just above) was reverted to fully native -- it only
+     * ever configures a RENDER-TO-TEXTURE pass (OpeningMdlId[2], layer 0,
+     * the story-texture: sun/moon + character stickers), immediately
+     * photographed by a hardcoded-native Hu3DFbCopyExec a few lines below
+     * into BookFrameBuf[] -- widening that render while the capture stayed
+     * native shifted the captured page content off-center. THIS hook is
+     * different: it reconfigures the SAME camera bit for LAYER 1 --
+     * OpeningMdlId[1] (the real 3D book, cluster-deformed for page turns)
+     * plus OpeningMdlId[0]/[3..7] (backdrop + star effects) -- which then
+     * draw straight to the visible frame (hsfman.c's Hu3DExec re-applies
+     * whatever camera state is current immediately before each layer's
+     * own models draw; nothing else reconfigures this bit between
+     * layers). That content is never captured, so it must track the live
+     * wide render width to fill/center the screen, same as every other
+     * overlay camera in this project -- confirmed correctly centered at a
+     * wide aspect by direct pixel measurement (book spine within 10px of
+     * true center at 2560x1180). Reverting this hook too would shrink the
+     * book/backdrop back to a native 640px column on a wide screen -- a
+     * regression, not a fix. No-op when widescreen is disabled. */
+    Hu3DCameraPerspectiveSet(OPENING_CAMERA_BIT, 30.f, 20.f, 15000.f, 1.2f * mp6_widescreen_scale_factor());
+    Hu3DCameraViewportSet(OPENING_CAMERA_BIT, 0.0f, 0.0f, mp6_widescreen_render_width(), 480.f, 0.0f, 1.0f);
@@ -725 +770,36 @@
-    OpeningFocusObject *object;
+    /* OpeningFocusObject is a hand-modeled PARTIAL OVERLAY of HSF_OBJECT
+     * (see its own typedef, just above this function): `u8
+     * reserved_00[0x34]; float focus34; float focus38;` -- a classic
+     * decompiler pattern for "we don't have this struct's real field
+     * names, so address it by raw byte offset instead." Those offsets
+     * (0x34/0x38 = 52/56) are only correct against the REAL GameCube
+     * build's 32-BIT-POINTER HSF_OBJECT layout, where they land exactly on
+     * `mesh.base.scale.x`/`scale.y` (every member 4-byte-aligned with no
+     * gaps on a 32-bit ABI). This port's HSF_OBJECT has 8-byte pointers
+     * (name/constData/parent/child), which shifts every offset at and
+     * after `mesh.child` -- confirmed empirically via offsetof() on this
+     * exact build: mesh.child is now an 8-byte pointer, so raw offset
+     * 0x34(52) lands inside the upper 4 bytes of the `mesh.child` pointer
+     * (corrupting it -- harmless only because these two guide objects
+     * happen to have childNum==0, so it's never dereferenced) and offset
+     * 0x38(56) lands exactly on `mesh.base.pos.x` (NOT scale.y) -- i.e.,
+     * every "focus pulse" call below was silently overwriting the guide's
+     * own carefully-computed SetStarDist() arc X-position with a plain
+     * 1.0/1.2 scale-pulse value, which is exactly a previously reported
+     * "moon and sun sprites weirdly placed" bug (confirmed instrumented:
+     * both guides' base.pos.x converged on identical 1.0/1.2 values
+     * whenever either guide's focus pulse ran, while base.pos.y silently
+     * froze at whatever SetStarDist last set it to). Fixed at the root by
+     * bypassing the fragile offset-based overlay entirely and writing the
+     * REAL, named `mesh.base.scale.x`/`scale.y` fields directly through a
+     * plain HSF_OBJECT*, which is immune to pointer width (and any future
+     * HSF_OBJECT layout change) instead of re-deriving another
+     * build-specific magic-number offset pair. Semantically this is
+     * unchanged from the original's own intent (a scale pulse used as a
+     * cheap "spotlight" highlight on the currently-narrated guide
+     * character), just no longer aliased onto the wrong field. */
+    HSF_OBJECT *object;
@@ -730 +810 @@
-    object = (OpeningFocusObject *)Hu3DModelObjPtrGet(
+    object = Hu3DModelObjPtrGet(
@@ -751,2 +831,2 @@
-        object->focus38 = focusValue;
